{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}} {{Use British English|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox cyclist | name = Peter Buckley | image = | caption = | fullname = Peter Buckley | nickname = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1944|8|2|df=yes}} | death_date = July 1969 | birth_place = {{IOM}} | height = | weight = | currentteam = | discipline = Road | role = Rider | ridertype = | amateuryears1 = | amateurteam1 = Manx Road Club | amateuryears2 = | amateurteam2 = Oldham Century Road Club | proyears1 = | proteam1 = | majorwins = | updated = 8 October 2008 | medaltemplates = {{MedalSport| Men's [[road bicycle racing|road cycling]] }} {{MedalCountry| {{IOM}} }} {{MedalCompetition | [[British Empire and Commonwealth Games]] }} {{MedalGold| [[1966 British Empire and Commonwealth Games|1966 Kingston]] | Road race }} }}
'''Peter Buckley''' (2 August 1944 – July 1969)<ref>England & Wales Death Register Index; Jul-Aug-Sep Quarter 1969; Peter Buckley; DOB: 2 Aug 1944; District registered: Leeds; Volume: 2c; Page: 940</ref> was a [[Isle of Man|Manx]] and [[British people|British]] [[racing cyclist]]. He was a gold medalist in the road race at the [[1966 British Empire and Commonwealth Games]] in [[Kingston, Jamaica]].
Buckley died in an accident whilst training in July 1969 when he hit a loose dog.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://manxroadclub.webs.com/clubhistory.htm| title=History | publisher=Manx Road Club| accessdate=2008-10-08}}</ref> The Peter Buckley Trophy was named in his honour, and is presented annually to the winner of the British junior national road race series winner.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://bikesy.co.uk/features/racing/british-junior-road-series-winners-the-definitive-list/| title=Junior National Series Winners| publisher=Bikesy| accessdate=2008-10-08}} </ref>
