{{Infobox stadium | name = Stade de Yamoussoukro | nickname = | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = Stade de Yamoussoukro.jpg | caption = | fullname = | former_names = | location = [[Yamoussoukro]], [[Côte d'Ivoire]] | coordinates = | broke_ground = 19 October 2018 | built = | opened = 2020 (expected) | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = Government of Ivory Coast | operator = | surface = Grass | scoreboard = | cost = $69 million | architect = [[SCAU Architectes]] | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = [[Sogea Atom]] | main_contractors = | capacity = 20,000 (expected) | suites = | record_attendance = | dimensions = 105m x 68m | acreage = | tenants = [[Côte d'Ivoire national football team]] }}
'''Stade de Yamoussoukro''', will be a football stadium, in [[Yamoussoukro]], [[Côte d'Ivoire]]. The stadium will have a capacity of 20,000 seats.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abidjan.net/h/622530.html|title=CAN 2021 : la Côte d’Ivoire lance un appel d’offres pour la construction d’infrastructures sportives et d’hébergements|date=20 September 2017|publisher=Abidjan.net|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://stadiumdb.com/news/2018/03/new_design_stade_de_yamoussoukro_for_afcon_2021|title=New design: Stade de Yamoussoukro for AFCON 2021|date=29 March 2018|publisher=StadiumDB}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scau.com/fr/article/scau-remporte-le-concours-de-conception-construction-du-stade-de-yamoussoukro|title=SCAU REMPORTE LE CONCOURS DE CONCEPTION CONSTRUCTION DU STADE DE YAMOUSSOUKRO.|date=7 March 2018|publisher=SCAU Architectes|language=fr}}</ref>
On 1 March 2018, an agreement between the government of Ivory Coast and an association formed of Alcor, Sogea-Satom, Egis and Baudin Chateauneuf was signed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sogea-satom.com/sogea-satom/sogea-satomv2.nsf/web/Actu_coup_denvoi_pour_le_stade_de_yamoussoukro.htm|title=COUP D’ENVOI POUR LE STADE DE YAMOUSSOUKRO|date=6 March 2018|publisher=Sogea Satom|language=fr}}</ref>
On 19 October 2018, the stadium was broke ground by Ivorian Prime Minister [[Amadou Gon Coulibaly]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sport-ivoire.ci/football-can/can-2021%C2%A0-amadou-gbon-coulibaly-lance-les-travaux|title=Amadou Gbon Coulibaly lance les travaux|publisher=Sport-Ivoire|date=19 October 2018|language=fr}}</ref>
The stadium is expected to host many matches of the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]].
